quran[24]{c,v,t,f}:
51,7,"By the heaven with its numerous forms: {1}",footnotes:1:The word hubuk in the original is also used for the paths and for the waves which are produced on the sand of the desert and the surface of stagnant water by the wind; it is also spoken for the curls in wavy hair. Here
51,8,"surely you are at variance (about the Hereafter); {1}",footnotes:1:The oath has been sworn by the sky of various appearances on this difference of views because of the similarity. That is
51,9,"though only those who are averse to the Truth will turn away from (believing in it). {1}",footnotes:1:The pronoun of anhu in this sentence either turns to the meting out of the rewards and punishments
51,10,"Doomed are the conjecturers {1}",footnotes:1:Here the Quran is warning man of an important truth. To judge or make an estimate on the basis of conjecture and speculation in the ordinary matters of worldly life may be useful to some extent
51,11,"who are steeped in ignorance and heedlessness. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
51,12,"They ask: “When will the Day of Judgement be?”"
51,13,"It will be the Day when they shall be scourged by the Fire {1}",footnotes:1:The disbelievers did not ask the question: “When will be the Resurrection” for the sake of seeking knowledge but for the purpose of taunt and ridicule. That is why they have been given such an answer. It is just like the taunting reaction of the wicked person who is admonished to desist from his immoral deeds
51,14,"(and be told): “Taste your ordeal! {1} This is what you were seeking to hasten.” {2}",footnotes:1:(1) Taste this torment of yours.The word fitnah gives two meanings here:
51,15,"As for the God-fearing, {1} they shall be in the midst of gardens and fountains,",footnotes:1:In this context the word muttaqi (the righteous) clearly implies those people who believed in the Hereafter when they were given the news of it by the Book of Allah and His Messenger
51,16,"joyously receiving what their Lord will have granted them. {1} Verily they did good works before (the coming of this Day):",footnotes:1:Literally: “Receiving what their Lord has given them”
51,17,"they used to sleep but little by night, {1}",footnotes:1:Some commentators have given this meaning of this verse: Seldom did it so happen that they spent the whole night sleeping and did not spend a part of it
51,18,"and would ask for forgiveness at dawn, {1}",footnotes:1:That is they did not belong to those who spent their nights in immoral and indecent acts and even then never thought of seeking Allah’s forgiveness. On the contrary
51,19,"and in their wealth there was a rightful share for him who would ask and for the destitute. {1}",footnotes:1:In other words
51,20,"There are many Signs on earth for those of sure faith, {1}",footnotes:1:The signs imply those proofs which testify to the possibility and necessity of the Hereafter. The earth’s own body and its structure
51,21,"and also in your own selves. {1} Do you not see?",footnotes:1:That is
51,22,"And in heaven is your provision and also what you are being promised. {1}",footnotes:1:By the heaven here is meant the heavens
51,23,"So, by the Lord of the heaven and the earth, this is certainly true, as true as the fact of your speaking."
51,24,"(O Prophet), did {1} the story of Abraham’s honoured guests reach you? {2}",footnotes:1:First
51,25,"When they came to him, they said: “Peace”; he said: “Peace also be to you; (you seem to be) a group of strangers.” {1}",footnotes:1:In view of the context in which this sentence has occurred
51,26,"Then he went back to his family {1} and brought a fat roasted calf {2}",footnotes:1:That is
51,27,"and laid it before them, saying: “Will you not eat?”"
51,28,"Then he became afraid of them. {1} They said: “Fear not,” and announced to him the good news of (the birth of) a boy endowed with knowledge. {2}",footnotes:1:That is
51,29,"So hearing his wife went forth shouting. She struck her face and exclaimed: “A barren old woman am I.” {1}",footnotes:1:That is
51,30,"They said: “So has your Lord said (that you shall have a boy). Surely He is Most Wise, All-Knowing.” {1}",footnotes:1:The object of this story is to tell that Allah will certainly reward His servant
